[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage facilitates the ability to replay specific segments or inputs of the dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This can be used in debugging or regenerating lost outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In database systems, this concept is closely related to data provenance, which involves maintaining records of inputs, entities, systems and processes that influence data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data provenance provides a historical record of data origins and transformations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage information includes technical metadata about data transformations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Enriched data lineage may include additional elements such as data quality test results, reference data, data models, business terminology, data stewardship information, program management details and enterprise systems associated with data points and transformations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage visualization tools often include masking features that allow users to focus on information relevant to specific use cases.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] To unify representations across disparate systems, metadata normalization or standardization may be required.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Representation broadly depends on the scope of the metadata management and reference point of interest.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage provides sources of the data and intermediate data flow hops from the reference point with **backward data lineage**, leading to the final destination's data points and its intermediate data flows with **forward data lineage**.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] These views can be combined with end-to-end **lineage** for a reference point that provides a complete audit trail of that data point of interest from sources to their final destinations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] As the data points or hops increase, the complexity of such representation becomes incomprehensible.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, the best feature of the data lineage view is the ability to simplify the view by temporarily masking unwanted peripheral data points.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Tools with the masking feature enable scalability of the view and enhance analysis with the best user experience for both technical and business users.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage also enables companies to trace sources of specific business data to track errors, implement changes in processes and implementing system migrations to save significant amounts of time and resources.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage can improve efficiency in business intelligence BI processes.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage can be represented visually to discover the data flow and movement from its source to destination via various changes and hops on its way in the enterprise environment.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This includes how the data is transformed along the way, how the representation and parameters change and how the data splits or converges after each hop.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A simple representation of the Data Lineage can be shown with dots and lines, where dots represent data containers for data points, and lines connecting them represent transformations the data undergoes between the data containers.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage can be visualized at various levels based on the granularity of the view.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] At a very high-level, data lineage is visualized as systems that the data interacts with before it reaches its destination.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] At its most granular, visualizations at the data point level can provide the details of the data point and its historical behavior, attribute properties and trends and data quality of the data passed through that specific data point in the data lineage.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The scope of the data lineage determines the volume of metadata required to represent its data lineage.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Usually, data governance and data management of an organization determine the scope of the data lineage based on their regulations, enterprise data management strategy, data impact, reporting attributes and critical data elements of the organization.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Distributed systems like Google Map Reduce, Microsoft Dryad, Apache Hadoop (an open-source project) and Google Pregel provide such platforms for businesses and users.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, even with these systems, Big Data analytics can take several hours, days or weeks to run, simply due to the data volumes involved.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, a ratings prediction algorithm for the Netflix Prize challenge took nearly 20 hours to execute on 50 cores, and a large-scale image processing task to estimate geographic information took 3 days to complete using 400 cores.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] "The Large Synoptic Survey Telescope is expected to generate terabytes of data every night and eventually store more than 50 petabytes, while in the bioinformatics sector, the 12 largest genome sequencing houses in the world now store petabytes of data apiece.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] It is very difficult for a data scientist to trace an unknown or an unanticipated result.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Big data analytics is the process of examining large data sets to uncover hidden patterns, unknown correlations, market trends, customer preferences and other useful business information.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Machine learning, among other algorithms, is used to transform and analyze the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Due to the large size of the data, there could be unknown features in the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The massive scale and unstructured nature of data, the complexity of these analytics pipelines, and long runtimes pose significant manageability and debugging challenges.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Even a single error in these analytics can be extremely difficult to identify and remove.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] While one may debug them by re-running the entire analytics through a debugger for stepwise debugging, this can be expensive due to the amount of time and resources needed.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Auditing and data validation are other major problems due to the growing ease of access to relevant data sources for use in experiments, the sharing of data between scientific communities and use of third-party data in business enterprises.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] As such, more cost-efficient ways of analyzing data intensive scale-able computing (DISC) are crucial to their continued effective use.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] According to an EMC/IDC study, 2.8 ZB of data were created and replicated in 2012.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Furthermore, the same study states that the digital universe will double every two years between now and 2020, and that there will be approximately 5.2 TB of data for every person in 2020.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Based on current technology, the storage of this much data will mean greater energy usage by data centers.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Unstructured data usually refers to information that doesn't reside in a traditional row-column database.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Unstructured data files often include text and multimedia content, such as e-mail messages, word processing documents, videos, photos, audio files, presentations, web pages and many other kinds of business documents.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] While these types of files may have an internal structure, they are still considered "unstructured" because the data they contain doesn't fit neatly into a database.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The amount of unstructured data in enterprises is growing many times faster than structured databases are growing.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Big data can include both structured and unstructured data, but IDC estimates that 90 percent of Big Data is unstructured data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The fundamental challenge of unstructured data sources is that they are difficult for non-technical business users and data analysts alike to unbox, understand and prepare for analytic use.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Beyond issues of structure, the sheer volume of this type of data contributes to such difficulty.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Because of this, current data mining techniques often leave out valuable information and make analyzing unstructured data laborious and expensive.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In today's competitive business environment, companies have to find and analyze the relevant data they need quickly.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The challenge is going through the volumes of data and accessing the level of detail needed, all at a high speed.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The challenge only grows as the degree of granularity increases.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Some vendors are using increased memory and parallel processing to crunch large volumes of data quickly.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Another method is putting data in-memory but using a grid computing approach, where many machines are used to solve a problem.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Both approaches allow organizations to explore huge data volumes.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Even with this level of sophisticated hardware and software, a few of the image processing tasks in large scale take a few days to few weeks.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Debugging of the data processing is extremely hard due to long run times.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A third approach of advanced data discovery solutions combines self-service data prep with visual data discovery, enabling analysts to simultaneously prepare and visualize data side-by-side in an interactive analysis environment offered by newer companies, such as Trifacta, Alteryx and others.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Another method to track data lineage is spreadsheet programs such as Excel that offer users cell-level lineage, or the ability to see which cells are dependent on another.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, the structure of the transformation is lost.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Similarly, ETL or mapping software provide transform-level lineage, yet this view typically doesn't display data and is too coarse-grained to distinguish between transforms that are logically independent (e.g. transforms that operate on distinct columns) or dependent.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Big Data platforms have a very complicated structure, where data is distributed across a vast range.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Typically, the jobs are mapped into several machines and results are later combined by the reduce operations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Debugging a Big Data pipeline becomes very challenging due to the very nature of the system.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] It will not be an easy task for the data scientist to figure out which machine's data has outliers and unknown features causing a particular algorithm to give unexpected results.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data provenance or data lineage can be used to make the debugging of Big Data pipeline easier.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This necessitates the collection of data about data transformations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The below section will explain data provenance in more detail.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In information systems, **data provenance** is information about the entities, activities, and agents involved in producing a piece of data; it records how data was derived and can be used to assess quality, reliability, and trustworthiness.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Classical database research distinguishes **why**, **where**, and **how** provenance and shows how these forms support tasks such as query debugging, view maintenance, confidence estimation, and annotation propagation.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In scientific workflows, provenance documents the derivation history from original sources through workflow steps, supporting reproducibility and reuse of results.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Open, implementation-oriented specifications such as **OpenLineage** model lineage in terms of jobs, runs, and datasets to enable automated capture from modern data pipelines.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Provenance is information about entities, activities and people involved in producing a piece of data or thing, which can be used to form assessments about its quality, reliability or trustworthiness.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] is defined as a record that describes the people, institutions, entities and activities involved in producing, influencing, or delivering a piece of data or something.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In particular, the provenance of information is crucial in deciding whether information is to be trusted, how it should be integrated with other diverse information sources, and how to give credit to its originators when reusing it.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In an open and inclusive environment such as the Web, where users find information that is often contradictory or questionable, provenance can help those users to make trust judgements.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Intuitively, for an operator T producing output o , lineage consists of triplets of form $\{i,T,o\}$ , where i is the set of inputs to T used to derive o .
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A query that finds the inputs deriving an output is called a *backward tracing query*, while one that finds the outputs produced by an input is called a *forward tracing query*.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Backward tracing is useful for debugging, while forward tracing is useful for tracking error propagation.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Tracing queries also form the basis for replaying an original dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, to efficiently use lineage in a DISC system, we need to be able to capture lineage at multiple levels (or granularities) of operators and data, capture accurate lineage for DISC processing constructs and be able to trace through multiple dataflow stages efficiently.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A DISC system consists of several levels of operators and data, and different use cases of lineage can dictate the level at which lineage needs to be captured.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lineage can be captured at the level of the job, using files and giving lineage tuples of form {IF i, M RJob, OF i }, lineage can also be captured at the level of each task, using records and giving, for example, lineage tuples of form {(k rr, v rr ), map, (k m, v m )}.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The first form of lineage is called coarse-grain lineage, while the second form is called fine-grain lineage.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Integrating lineage across different granularities enables users to ask questions such as "Which file read by a MapReduce job produced this particular output record?" and can be useful in debugging across different operators and data granularities within a dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] To capture end-to-end lineage in a DISC system, we use the Ibis model, which introduces the notion of containment hierarchies for operators and data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Specifically, Ibis proposes that an operator can be contained within another and such a relationship between two operators is called *operator containment*.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Operator containment implies that the contained (or child) operator performs a part of the logical operation of the containing (or parent) operator.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, a MapReduce task is contained in a job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Similar containment relationships exist for data as well, Known as data containment.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data containment implies that the contained data is a subset of the containing data (superset).
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Data lineage systems can be categorized as either eager or lazy.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Eager collection systems capture the entire lineage of the data flow at run time.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The kind of lineage they capture may be coarse-grain or fine-grain, but they do not require any further computations on the data flow after its execution.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lazy lineage collection typically captures only coarse-grain lineage at run time.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] These systems incur low capture overheads due to the small amount of lineage they capture.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, to answer fine-grain tracing queries, they must replay the data flow on all (or a large part) of its input and collect fine-grain lineage during the replay.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This approach is suitable for forensic systems, where a user wants to debug an observed bad output.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Eager fine-grain lineage collection systems incur higher capture overheads than lazy collection systems.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, they enable sophisticated replay and debugging.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] An actor is an entity that transforms data; it may be a Dryad vertex, individual map and reduce operators, a MapReduce job, or an entire dataflow pipeline.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Actors act as black boxes and the inputs and outputs of an actor are tapped to capture lineage in the form of associations, where an association is a triplet $\{i,T,o\}$ that relates an input i with an output o for an actor T .
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The instrumentation thus captures lineage in a dataflow one actor at a time, piecing it into a set of associations for each actor.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The system developer needs to capture the data an actor reads (from other actors) and the data an actor writes (to other actors).
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, a developer can treat the Hadoop Job Tracker as an actor by recording the set of files read and written by each job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Association is a combination of the inputs, outputs and the operation itself.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The operation is represented in terms of a black box also known as the actor.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The associations describe the transformations that are applied to the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The associations are stored in the association tables.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Each unique actor is represented by its association table.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] An association itself looks like {i, T, o} where i is the set of inputs to the actor T and o is the set of outputs produced by the actor.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Associations are the basic units of Data Lineage.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Individual associations are later clubbed together to construct the entire history of transformations that were applied to the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Big data systems increase capacity by adding new hardware or software entities into the distributed system.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This process is called *horizontal scaling*.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The distributed system acts as a single entity at the logical level even though it comprises multiple hardware and software entities.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The system should continue to maintain this property after horizontal scaling.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] An important advantage of horizontal scalability is that it can provide the ability to increase capacity on the fly.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The biggest plus point is that horizontal scaling can be done using commodity hardware.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The horizontal scaling feature of Big Data systems should be taken into account while creating the architecture of lineage store.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This is essential because the lineage store itself should also be able to scale in parallel with the Big Data system.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The number of associations and amount of storage required to store lineage will increase with the increase in size and capacity of the system.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The architecture of Big Data systems makes use of a single lineage store not appropriate and impossible to scale.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The immediate solution to this problem is to distribute the lineage store itself.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The best-case scenario is to use a local lineage store for every machine in the distributed system network.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This allows the lineage store also to scale horizontally.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In this design, the lineage of data transformations applied to the data on a particular machine is stored on the local lineage store of that specific machine.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The lineage store typically stores association tables.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Each actor is represented by its own association table.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The rows are the associations themselves, and the columns represent inputs and outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] It allows horizontal scaling of the lineage store.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] If a single centralized lineage store was used, then this information had to be carried over the network, which would cause additional network latency.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The network latency is also avoided by the use of a distributed lineage store.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The information stored in terms of associations needs to be combined by some means to get the data flow of a particular job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In a distributed system a job is broken down into multiple tasks.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] One or more instances run a particular task.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The results produced on these individual machines are later combined to finish the job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Tasks running on different machines perform multiple transformations on the data in the machine.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] All the transformations applied to the data on a machine is stored in the local lineage store of that machines.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This information needs to be combined to get the lineage of the entire job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The lineage of the entire job should help the data scientist understand the data flow of the job and he/she can use the data flow to debug the Big Data pipeline.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The data flow is reconstructed in 3 stages.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The first stage of the data flow reconstruction is the computation of the association tables.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The association tables exist for each actor in each local lineage store.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The entire association table for an actor can be computed by combining these individual association tables.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This is generally done using a series of equality joins based on the actors themselves.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In few scenarios the tables might also be joined using inputs as the key.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Indexes can also be used to improve the efficiency of a join.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The joined tables need to be stored on a single instance or a machine to further continue processing.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] There are multiple schemes that are used to pick a machine where a join would be computed.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The easiest one being the one with minimum CPU load.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Space constraints should also be kept in mind while picking the instance where join would happen.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The second step in data flow reconstruction is computing an association graph from the lineage information.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The graph represents the steps in the data flow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The actors act as vertices and the associations act as edges.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Each actor T is linked to its upstream and downstream actors in the data flow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] An upstream actor of T is one that produced the input of T, while a downstream actor is one that consumes the output of T.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Containment relationships are always considered while creating the links.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The graph consists of three types of links or edges.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The simplest link is an explicitly specified link between two actors.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] These links are explicitly specified in the code of a machine learning algorithm.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] When an actor is aware of its exact upstream or downstream actor, it can communicate this information to lineage API.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This information is later used to link these actors during the tracing query.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, each map instance knows the exact record reader instance whose output it consumes.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Developers can attach data flow archetypes to each logical actor.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A data flow archetype explains how the child types of an actor type arrange themselves in a data flow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] With the help of this information, one can infer a link between each actor of a source type and a destination type.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, the map actor type is the source for reduce, and vice versa.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The system infers this from the data flow archetypes and duly links map instances with reduce instances.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, there may be several MapReduce jobs in the data flow and linking all map instances with all reduce instances can create false links.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] To prevent this, such links are restricted to actor instances contained within a common actor instance of a containing (or parent) actor type.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, map and reduce instances are only linked to each other if they belong to the same job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In distributed systems, sometimes there are implicit links, which are not specified during execution.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] For example, an implicit link exists between an actor that wrote to a file and another actor that read from it.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Such links connect actors which use a common data set for execution.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The dataset is the output of the first actor and the input of the actor follows it.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The final step in the data flow reconstruction is the topological sorting of the association graph.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The directed graph created in the previous step is topologically sorted to obtain the order in which the actors have modified the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This record of modifications by the different actors involved is used to track the data flow of the Big Data pipeline or task.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This is the most crucial step in Big Data debugging.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The captured lineage is combined and processed to obtain the data flow of the pipeline.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The data flow helps the data scientist or a developer to look deeply into the actors and their transformations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This step allows the data scientist to figure out the part of the algorithm that is generating the unexpected output.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A Big Data pipeline can go wrong in two broad ways.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The first is a presence of a suspicious actor in the dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The second is the existence of outliers in the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The first case can be debugged by tracing the dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] By using lineage and data-flow information together a data scientist can figure out how the inputs are converted into outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] During the process actors that behave unexpectedly can be caught.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Either these actors can be removed from the data flow, or they can be augmented by new actors to change the dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The improved dataflow can be replayed to test the validity of it.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Debugging faulty actors include recursively performing coarse-grain replay on actors in the dataflow, which can be expensive in resources for long dataflows.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Another approach is to manually inspect lineage logs to find anomalies, which can be tedious and time-consuming across several stages of a dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Furthermore, these approaches work only when the data scientist can discover bad outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] To debug analytics without known bad outputs, the data scientist needs to analyze the dataflow for suspicious behavior in general.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, often, a user may not know the expected normal behavior and cannot specify predicates.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This section describes a debugging methodology for retrospectively analyzing lineage to identify faulty actors in a multi-stage dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] We believe that sudden changes in an actor's behavior, such as its average selectivity, processing rate or output size, is characteristic of an anomaly.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lineage can reflect such changes in actor behavior over time and across different actor instances.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, mining lineage to identify such changes can be useful in debugging faulty actors in a dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The second problem i.e. the existence of outliers can also be identified by running the dataflow step wise and looking at the transformed outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The data scientist finds a subset of outputs that are not in accordance with the rest of outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The inputs which are causing these bad outputs are outliers in the data.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This problem can be solved by removing the set of outliers from the data and replaying the entire dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] It can also be solved by modifying the machine learning algorithm by adding, removing or moving actors in the dataflow.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The changes in the dataflow are successful if the replayed dataflow does not produce bad outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Although the utilization of data lineage methodologies represents a novel approach to the debugging of Big Data pipelines, the process is not straightforward.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A number of challenges must be addressed, including the scalability of the lineage store, the fault tolerance of the lineage store, the accurate capture of lineage for black box operators, and numerous other considerations.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] These challenges must be carefully evaluated in order to develop a realistic design for data lineage capture, taking into account the inherent trade-offs between them.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] DISC systems are primarily batch processing systems designed for high throughput.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] They execute several jobs per analytics, with several tasks per job.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The overall number of operators executing at any time in a cluster can range from hundreds to thousands depending on the cluster size.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lineage capture for these systems must be able scale to both large volumes of data and numerous operators to avoid being a bottleneck for the DISC analytics.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lineage capture systems must also be fault tolerant to avoid rerunning data flows to capture lineage.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] At the same time, they must also accommodate failures in the DISC system.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] To do so, they must be able to identify a failed DISC task and avoid storing duplicate copies of lineage between the partial lineage generated by the failed task and duplicate lineage produced by the restarted task.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] A lineage system should also be able to gracefully handle multiple instances of local lineage systems going down.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This can be achieved by storing replicas of lineage associations in multiple machines.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] The replica can act like a backup in the event of the real copy being lost.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lineage systems for DISC dataflows must be able to capture accurate lineage across black-box operators to enable fine-grain debugging.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Although producing highly accurate lineage, such techniques can incur significant time overheads for capture or tracing, and it may be preferable to instead trade some accuracy for better performance.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage collection system for DISC dataflows that can capture lineage from arbitrary operators with reasonable accuracy, and without significant overheads in capture or tracing.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Tracing is essential for debugging, during which a user can issue multiple tracing queries.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, it is important that tracing has fast turnaround times.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. can perform efficient backward tracing queries for MapReduce dataflows but are not generic to different DISC systems and do not perform efficient forward queries.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Lipstick, a lineage system for Pig, while able to perform both backward and forward tracing, is specific to Pig and SQL operators and can only perform coarse-grain tracing for black-box operators.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that enables efficient forward and backward tracing for generic DISC systems and dataflows with black-box operators.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Replaying only specific inputs or portions of dataflow is crucial for efficient debugging and simulating what-if scenarios.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. present a methodology for a lineage-based refresh, which selectively replays updated inputs to recompute affected outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] This is useful during debugging for re-computing outputs when a bad input has been fixed.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] However, sometimes a user may want to remove the bad input and replay the lineage of outputs previously affected by the error to produce error-free outputs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Another use of replay in debugging involves replaying bad inputs for stepwise debugging (called selective replay).
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Current approaches to using lineage in DISC systems do not address these.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that can perform both exclusive and selective replays to address different debugging needs.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] One of the primary debugging concerns in DISC systems is identifying faulty operators.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] In long dataflows with several hundreds of operators or tasks, manual inspection can be tedious and prohibitive.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] Even if lineage is used to narrow the subset of operators to examine, the lineage of a single output can still span several operators.
[src:dagster/data-lineage] There is a need for an inexpensive automated debugging system, which can substantially narrow the set of potentially faulty operators, with reasonable accuracy, to minimize the amount of manual examination required.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:dagster/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Dagster is a data orchestrator built for data engineers, with integrated lineage, observability, a declarative programming model, and best-in-class testability.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Build your first Dagster pipeline in our Quickstart tutorial.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Learn about how thinking in assets can help you manage your data better.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Learn about Dagster Plus, our managed offering that includes a hosted Dagster instance and many more features.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Join our Slack community to talk with other Dagster users, use our AI-powered chatbot, and get help with Dagster.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Star our GitHub repository and follow our development through GitHub Discussions.
[src:dagster/docs-dagster-io] Learn Dagster through interactive courses and hands-on tutorials.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:dagster/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:dagster/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:dagster/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
